{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}} {{Use Australian English|date=September 2016}} {{BLP primary sources|date=August 2015}} '''Sharon Beder''' is an honorary professor in the Faculty of Arts at the [[University of Wollongong]] in [[New South Wales]], Australia.<ref name="Contributors-dn-7(2)">[http://www.democracynature.org/vol7/contributors_2.htm "Contributors,"] ''[[Democracy & Nature]]'', Vol. 7, No. 2 (July 2001). Retrieved 3 June 2014.</ref> Her research has focused on how power relationships are maintained and challenged, particularly by corporations and professions. She has written 10 books, and many articles, book chapters and conference papers, as well as designing teaching resources and educational websites.<ref name="Contributors-dn-7(2)"/>
==Training==
Beder initially trained and worked as a [[civil engineer]] before becoming interested in the social, political and philosophical aspects of engineering and then environmental politics. She completed a PhD in [[Science and Technology Studies]] at the [[University of NSW]] in 1989 based on research into the process of engineering decision-making using a case study on the development of Sydney's sewerage system.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}
==Appointments==
Before joining the University of Wollongong in 1992, Beder was Environmental Education Co-ordinator at the [[University of Sydney]]. She has also been Chairperson of the Environmental Engineering Branch of the [[Engineers Australia|Institution of Engineers]], Sydney, President of the Society for Social Responsibility in Engineering, and a director of the Earth Foundation Australia.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}
==Awards==
Beder was included in a list of "Australia's most influential engineers", published by ''Engineers Australia'' in 2004.<ref>Dietrich Georg, "Shaping Our Material World", Engineers Australia, June 2004, p. 31.</ref> She was also included in ''Bulletin Magazine's'' "Smart 100" in 2003.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2003/10/22/1066631438758.html|title=Australia's Smart 100 - National|last=Source: The Bulletin|date=22 October 2003|website=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|access-date=2016-03-28}}</ref> Awards received include:
*High Commendation for IEAust Award for Cultural Change in Engineering Education, 1998{{citation needed|date=March 2016}} *[[Michael Daley Award]] for Excellence in Science, Technology and Engineering Journalism, 1992 <ref>"Daley Award to Herald Writer Again", Sydney Morning Herald, 2 December 1992, p. 8.</ref> *Media Prize, Australian Surfers Hall of Fame, 1990.<ref>Willcox, Kirk, "Californian Challenge", Sydney Morning Herald, 19 April 1990, p. 15.</ref>
